1. What is UAT? Who will do the testing and what is the purpose?

UAT (User Acceptance Testing) is the final stage of testing where the application is tested by end users or business stakeholders.

End Users
Clients/Customers
Business Users
Product Owners

Purpose of UAT:

To verify that the application meets business requirements.
To ensure the system is ready for production.
To get approval from the customer before release.
2. What is the difference between Functional and Non-Functional Testing?

Functional Testing:

Checks whether the application functions correctly according to requirements.
Focuses on features and business logic.

Examples:

Login Testing
Registration Testing
Payment Testing

Non-Functional Testing:

Checks the performance and quality of the application.
Focuses on how well the system works.

Examples:

Performance Testing
Security Testing
Load Testing
3. Load Testing will come under Functional or Non-Functional Testing? Why?

Load Testing comes under Non-Functional Testing.

Reason:
Load testing checks how the application performs when many users access it at the same time. It measures response time, stability, and performance rather than checking business functionality.

Example:
Testing whether a website can handle 1,000 users simultaneously.

4. What is Exploratory Testing and when do we do it?

Exploratory Testing is a type of testing where the tester explores the application without predefined test cases.

When is it performed?

When requirements are unclear.
When there is limited time to prepare test cases.
After formal testing to find hidden defects.

Purpose:
To discover bugs that may not be found through regular test cases.

5. What is Black Box Testing and how does it differ from White Box Testing?

Black Box Testing:
Black Box Testing is a testing method where the tester checks the application's functionality without knowing the internal code.

Example:
Testing a login page by entering valid and invalid credentials.

White Box Testing:
White Box Testing is a testing method where the tester has knowledge of the internal code and tests the program's logic and structure.

Difference:
Black Box Testing	                      White Box Testing
No knowledge of code is required.	      Knowledge of code is required.
Focuses on functionality.	              Focuses on code structure and logic.
Mostly performed by testers.	          Mostly performed by developers.
Tests inputs and outputs.	              Tests code paths and conditions
